ce:section.ce:para:
The change of tracer concentration in the effluent of the four typical core floods is shown in Fig. 4
                        . It can be found that all floods had displayed similar profiles of the normalized tracer concentration. At 3 PVI, the C/Cinj of Flood #1 for C-dots-CAHS is 0.84, which is lower than that in other floods. The lower C/Cinj could be attributed to the heterogeneity of the core plugs. Indiana limestone is much more heterogeneous than most sandstone and owns a dual-mode pore-throat size distribution. Though all adopted outcrops were drilled from the same block of Indiana limestone, they still had trivial differences in permeability and pore throat distribution, which further induced the change of effluent profiles. According to the methods mentioned above, the retention of all investigated tracers is found to be 0 mg/g, including C-dots-Pristine in Flood #4. Besides, no significant permeability change was noticed in the cores (Table 2
                        ), suggesting the tracers had superior transport performance in the porous medium.
